"""
mkt-context | judges | ch18–19 fill
present: ch18:v1,7,14,30,31; ch19:v1,15,22,29,30 — 51 missing verses
run: python3 scripts/zc-context-judges-18-19-fill.py

Ch18: Danite migration — tribal geography, divination customs, Tell Dan archaeology
Ch19: Gibeah crime — hospitality customs, Sodom typology, anti-Sodom narrative structure
Completes Judges context (19/21 → 21/21)
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).resolve().parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{layer}' / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{layer}' / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

JUDGES = {
  "18": {
    "2": "<p>The Danite scouts are 'men of valor' (<em>ʾanšê ḥayil</em>) sent to explore the land — the same reconnaissance function used in the Conquest (Josh 2:1; Num 13:17). The five men from Zorah and Eshtaol represent the westernmost Danite settlement; the tribal territory assigned to Dan in Josh 19:40-48 included these cities but proved impossible to hold (cf. 1:34). The necessity of sending scouts to reconnoiter northern territory reveals the extent of Dan's failure: they are effectively starting the conquest over, decades after the initial tribal assignments had been made.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The scouts 'recognized the voice of the young man the Levite' — they knew him, or at least recognized his accent or dialect as that of a Levite trained in a particular sanctuary tradition. Ancient priestly dialects and liturgical speech patterns would have been distinctive markers. Their questions — 'Who brought you here? What are you doing here? What is your business here?' — are the standard interrogation of a stranger at a private dwelling; the threefold questioning establishes the Levite's status before they exploit his services. The encounter is opportunistic: they were not looking for a priest but found one.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The Levite explains: Micah hired him as his personal priest (<em>kōhēn</em>). The private employment of a Levite as a household priest was technically irregular — Levites were tribal-class religious specialists, not private chaplains. Micah's arrangement (ch17:10: 'Be to me a father and priest, and I will give you ten pieces of silver a year') represents the privatization of Levitical ministry that happens when the central sanctuary system breaks down. The Levite's willingness to serve as a household chaplain for pay indicates the economic precarity of Levites without tribal income from the central cult (cf. Deut 14:27-29 on supporting Levites).</p>",
    "5": "<p>'Please inquire of God, that we may know whether the journey on which we are going will succeed.' The request for a divine oracle before embarking on a mission reflects standard ancient Near Eastern procedure: before major military or exploratory undertakings, one consulted the divine through a priest-mediator. The Urim and Thummim (Exod 28:30; Num 27:21) were the legitimate Israelite oracle mechanism; Micah's private ephod (ch17:5) was an unauthorized substitute. The Danites are essentially shopping for a favorable oracle from a priest of uncertain legitimacy, using illegitimate cultic apparatus — the entire sequence is religiously problematic from start to finish.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The Levite's oracle — 'Go in peace. The journey on which you go is under the eye of YHWH' — is a favorable divine-travel oracle of the type frequently requested before journeys (cf. Gen 24:40; 1 Sam 1:17). The problem is that the oracle is given through stolen cultic objects (v18: 'the ephod, the teraphim, and the carved image, and the metal image') and an improperly-ordained priest — making its divine authority highly questionable. The narrative never directly evaluates the oracle's validity but embeds the reader's doubt in the surrounding narrative of cultic irregularity.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The scouts return to Zorah and Eshtaol — their base — and report to their kinsmen. The phrasing 'their brothers said to them, What do you report?' reflects the formal debriefing structure of military reconnaissance: the scouts report, the leadership evaluates, the assembly decides. The parallel with Joshua's spy mission (Josh 2:23-24: 'They came to Joshua and told him everything that had happened to them') establishes the Danite mission as a delayed echo of the initial conquest — but now acting on tribal initiative rather than divine command.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'Arise, and let us go up against them. For we have seen the land, and behold, it is very good. And will you do nothing? Do not be slow to go, to enter in and possess the land.' The rhetorical urgency — repeated imperatives, the reproach 'do nothing,' the accusation of slowness — reflects the tribal assembly's impatience after years of territorial failure. The Conquest vocabulary ('possess the land,' <em>lārešet ʾet-hāʾāreṣ</em>) deliberately echoes Joshua's commissioning speech (Josh 1:11) but is now applied to an unauthorized private tribal migration rather than a divinely-commanded occupation. The form is right; the authorization is absent.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'When you go, you will come to an unsuspecting people. The land is spacious, for God has given it into your hands, a place where there is no lack of anything that is in the earth.' The claim that 'God has given it into your hands' is presented as the scouts' evaluation rather than a divine oracle — they are interpreting circumstances as divine authorization. This appropriation of conquest-gift language for self-motivated territorial expansion is a significant theological distortion. Genuine divine gift-language in the conquest narratives comes through prophetic or priestly oracles (Josh 1:2-3; 6:2); here it is a tribal committee's marketing pitch.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Six hundred armed Danites depart from Zorah and Eshtaol — a combat-size force, not a settlement migration (though families follow). The number 600 recurs in connection with Dan specifically: 600 Danites appear again in ch20:47 fleeing to the rock of Rimmon. Whether this reflects an actual tribal force size or a conventional number for a military unit is debated; 600 was also Saul's force at Michmash (1 Sam 13:15) and the Philistine garrison (1 Sam 13:5 LXX). The tribal force is equipped for war, not merely for relocation — they are conquerors, not settlers, despite the peaceful framing of their departure.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The camp at Kiriath-jearim is called Mahaneh-dan ('camp of Dan') — and the narrator notes 'it is so to this day.' The use of this etiological formula ('to this day') appears throughout Judges at sites whose names commemorate specific events (cf. 1:26; 2:5). The double naming of the Mahaneh-dan camp — once here and once in 13:25, during the Samson narrative — links the two stories geographically: the Danite scouts pass through the same territory where Samson will later operate, connecting the tribe's northward migration with Samson's Philistine-area birth.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The 600 Danites pass through Ephraim to Micah's house — a detour into the hill country rather than taking a direct northern route. The deliberate routing through Micah's location is not coincidental; the scouts had identified his shrine as a resource to be acquired. The narrative's pacing creates suspense: the reader who has followed the shrine's establishment through ch17 now watches the Danites approach it, knowing what the five scouts have already planned (v2-6). The long journey narrative (six hundred men marching through Ephraim) makes the pillage of one household feel all the more disproportionate.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The five scouts lead the 600 to Micah's house and 'greeted him.' The polite greeting (<em>lĕšālōm</em> — asking about his welfare/peace) is immediately followed by looting — the most pointed irony of the chapter. Ancient hospitality conventions included formal greeting protocols; their violation by the subsequent theft makes the Danites' behavior comparable to Gibeah's hospitality-violation in ch19. The entire narrative arc of Judges 17-21 is structured around progressive violations of the hospitality code that held Iron Age society together: from Micah's irregular shrine (ch17) to Danite theft (ch18) to Gibeah's gang assault (ch19).</p>",
    "16": "<p>The 600 armed men stand at the city gate while the five scouts enter and take the cultic objects. The armed force stationed at the gate is not for battle but for intimidation — they are blocking the exit while the theft occurs. This staged robbery, with a military show of force ensuring no resistance, reflects the violence underlying the Danite migration: they are not merely relocating but taking what they want by force from a weaker neighbor. The military-backed theft of sacred objects has a precise parallel in the Neo-Assyrian imperial practice of carrying away the gods of conquered peoples — a practice that would later devastate Israel itself (2 Kings 17; Isa 36:18-20).</p>",
    "17": "<p>The five scouts take the carved image, ephod, teraphim, and metal image while the 600 stand guard. The specific list of four cultic items (earlier listed in 17:5 as the contents of Micah's shrine) functions as an inventory that marks the theft's completeness — nothing is left behind. In ANE terms, the capture of a city's or shrine's divine images was the equivalent of capturing the divine patron's power; the Danites are not merely stealing valuables but appropriating the divine protection that Micah had installed. This is why Micah's lament in v24 is so pointed: 'You have taken away my gods that I made.'</p>",
    "18": "<p>When the Levite asks what they are doing, the Danites respond: 'Be silent; put your hand over your mouth and come with us, and be to us a father and a priest.' The command to silence (<em>hašqēt śîm yādĕkā ʿal-pîkā</em>) is an authoritative silencing — the gesture of putting the hand over the mouth appears in Job 21:5; 29:9 as a gesture of respectful silence before a superior. The Danites are offering the Levite a promotion (from household priest to tribal priest) while simultaneously silencing his moral objection. The offer replicates Micah's original offer (17:10) but at tribal scale — and the Levite accepts it for the same reason: career advancement.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'Is it better for you to be priest to the house of one man, or to be priest to a tribe and family in Israel?' The Danites' offer to the Levite reframes the theft as an opportunity for him — he should be grateful for the upgrade from household to tribal priesthood. The argument is purely careerist: the legitimacy of the shrine, the ethics of the theft, and the Levite's obligations to Micah are all irrelevant to the calculation. The narrative is deeply ironic: the Levite, who should be the religious-ethical anchor of the situation, is the most morally compromised figure in it — he accepts stolen cult objects and the offer of tribal employment without a moment of resistance.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'And the heart of the priest was glad.' The Levite's joy at the Danite offer is the narrative's most damning verdict on his character — he is glad to go, unconcerned about the theft, the moral status of his new employers, or his obligations to Micah. The 'glad heart' (<em>wayyiṭab lēb hakōhēn</em>) is the same idiom used for genuine celebration in other contexts (Ruth 3:7; 1 Sam 25:36) but here marks religious compromise as personal satisfaction. He takes the ephod, teraphim, and carved image and 'goes into the midst of the people' — fully embedded with the Danite force, complicit in every aspect of the operation.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The Danites put their 'little ones, livestock, and goods in front of them' — a military formation that placed the non-combatants and valuables in the protected center/front of the column, with the armed fighters at the rear to prevent pursuit. This tactical arrangement anticipates exactly the confrontation of vv22-26, where Micah and his neighbors pursue and the armed Danites turn to face them. The placement of valuables at the front and fighters at the rear is a standard rearguard formation used when retreating with plunder.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Micah and his neighbors pursue the Danites and call out to them. The fact that 'the men in the houses near Micah's house were called out' — a local neighborhood response — suggests that Micah's shrine was a recognized community institution, not merely a private household chapel. Neighbors with a stake in the local cultic center respond to the theft with communal solidarity. The pursuit is possible because the Danite force has not moved quickly — the families, livestock, and goods (v21) significantly slow the column, giving Micah time to muster his neighbors and catch up.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The Danites ask Micah: 'What is the matter with you, that you come with such a company?' The rhetorical question (<em>mah-lĕkā kî nizʿāqtā</em>) treats Micah's pursuit as the unreasonable action — as if the victim's indignation is the problem rather than the theft. The reversal of victim and aggressor in the Danites' framing is characteristic of the powerful dealing with the weak throughout Judges: the seven-nation list of ch3 demanded deference; the Danite force demands the same. Micah is being asked to accept a power differential and simply go home.</p>",
    "24": "<p>'You have taken my gods that I made and the priest, and gone away, and what do I have left? How then do you ask me, What is the matter with you?' Micah's lament — 'my gods that I made' (<em>ʾet-ʾĕlōhay ʾăšer-ʿāśîtî</em>) — is the theological indictment of the entire Micah shrine narrative: the gods are handmade, man-manufactured objects. The phrase echoes the prophetic polemic against idols (Isa 44:9-20: 'He makes a god and worships it; he makes it a carved image and falls down before it'; Ps 115:4: 'Their idols are silver and gold, the work of human hands'). Micah himself unwittingly identifies the fundamental problem with his religion: gods that humans make are gods that other humans can take.</p>",
    "25": "<p>'You had better not let your voice be heard among us, lest angry fellows fall upon you, and you lose your life with the lives of your household.' The Danites' threat against Micah reveals the power dynamic in its starkest form: they have 600 armed men; he has himself and his neighbors. The instruction to suppress his grievance under threat of violence is the suppression of legitimate covenant justice by force. Ecclesiastes 5:8 reflects on this pattern: 'If you see in a province the oppression of the poor and the violation of justice and righteousness, do not be amazed at the matter, for the high official is watched by a higher, and there are yet higher ones over them.' The Danites are the higher power; Micah has no court of appeal.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Micah sees that the Danites are too strong and turns back. The conclusion — the powerless victim can do nothing — is a realistic social observation embedded in the narrative's theological indictment of the period. Micah had obtained a Levite through irregular means (17:12), installed unauthorized cult objects, and created a private shrine outside the covenant structures; he is now the victim of exactly the same disregard for covenant norms that he had earlier practiced. The cycle of covenant-violation produces a society in which no one's rights are secure because there is 'no king in Israel' and everyone does what is right in their own eyes (17:6; 18:1).</p>",
    "27": "<p>The Danites take what Micah had made and come to Laish — 'to a people quiet and unsuspecting, and struck them with the edge of the sword and burned the city with fire.' The destruction of Laish is a military atrocity: a peaceful, isolated population with no defensive alliances is annihilated. The contrast with the Conquest narratives is stark: Joshua's campaigns were divinely commanded (Deut 7:1-2; Josh 6:17), targeted specific covenant-defiled populations, and included specific terms. The Danite campaign is unauthorized, motivated by tribal land-hunger, and directed against 'quiet and unsuspecting' civilians who posed no threat. The Conquest's moral framework is being replicated without its covenant justification.</p>",
    "28": "<p>'There was no deliverer because it was far from Sidon, and they had no dealings with anyone.' Laish's isolation is both its attractiveness to the Danites (no powerful neighbors to retaliate) and its tragedy (no one to come to its aid). The note that Laish was 'in the valley that belongs to Beth-rehob' provides geographical context: Beth-rehob was a small Aramean state in the upper Jordan valley. Laish/Dan at Tell Dan sits at the foot of Mount Hermon near the headwaters of the Jordan — its geographic remoteness from both Phoenician coastal power and Israelite tribal centers made it the ideal undefended target for a displaced tribe.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The Danites name the city Dan after their ancestor — erasing Laish's identity and inscribing Danite identity on the site. The name-imposition is a standard act of territorial possession in the ancient world: colonizers rename places to assert ownership (cf. the Israelite renaming of Kiriath-arba to Hebron, 1:10; and the renaming of Hormah/Zephath, 1:17). The renaming also signals the beginning of the cultic establishment: the place-name Dan will become inseparable from the illegitimate shrine, so that the site itself carries the theological condemnation embedded in its founding narrative.</p>"
  },
  "19": {
    "2": "<p>The concubine 'played the whore against him' (<em>wattizneh ʿālaw</em>) and returned to her father's house — the precise nature of the offense is debated. The verb <em>zānāh</em> (to commit sexual immorality) is the standard infidelity term; the Septuagint reads 'she became angry with him,' suggesting a textual or interpretive variant. The Levite's journey to retrieve her establishes the narrative's first hospitality scene: the father-in-law's extended, almost excessive, hospitality (vv4-9) will be contrasted starkly with Gibeah's total failure of hospitality. The chapter structurally juxtaposes excessive welcoming (the father-in-law) with violent rejection (the men of Gibeah).</p>",
    "3": "<p>The Levite travels 'to speak tenderly to her and bring her back' (<em>lĕdabbēr ʿal-libbāh</em>, to speak to her heart) — an idiom of gentle persuasion used in Gen 50:21 (Joseph to his brothers) and Isa 40:2 (comfort for Jerusalem). The presence of two donkeys and a servant indicates the Levite is a man of some means; the servant becomes a significant figure later (v11-12) as the one who suggests stopping at Jebus. When the father sees the Levite, 'he rejoiced to meet him' — a warm reception that sets up the extended hospitality of the following days and contrasts with the cold reception at Gibeah.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The father-in-law 'retained him' for three extra days — the language of hospitality's power to extend itself. Ancient near Eastern hospitality customs were elaborate and obligatory: a guest's needs were entirely the host's responsibility; refusing to let a guest leave before they were fully rested, fed, and equipped was a mark of honor, not coercion. The three days of extended hospitality echo other biblical narratives where the three-day period marks preparation for a journey of significance (Gen 40:12-13; Josh 1:11; Jonah 1:17). The father-in-law's generosity is genuine; its contrast with Gibeah's hostility will be structurally loaded.</p>",
    "5": "<p>On the fourth morning the Levite prepares to depart and the father-in-law urges him to 'strengthen your heart with a piece of bread' before the journey. The phrase 'strengthen your heart' (<em>sĕʿad libbĕkā</em>) appears also in Gen 18:5 (Abraham's hospitality to the three visitors) and Ps 104:15 (wine 'to gladden the heart of man'). The eating together is hospitality's essential act — sharing bread constitutes a bond. The father-in-law is performing the full ancient hospitality protocol with scrupulous care, which will make Gibeah's failure all the more catastrophic by contrast.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The father-in-law persuades the Levite to stay another day: 'Please stay the night and let your heart be merry.' The extended delay created by the father-in-law's hospitality is the narrative's mechanism for ensuring the Levite arrives in Gibeah at nightfall rather than during the day — timing that makes his vulnerability and the need for shelter urgent. Ancient travel was not done after dark; night in an unfamiliar city without hospitality arranged in advance was genuinely dangerous. The narrative's irony deepens: excessive hospitality (the father-in-law) directly causes the encounter with non-existent hospitality (Gibeah).</p>",
    "7": "<p>The Levite prepares to leave again on the fifth morning, and the father-in-law urges him a second time. The threefold repetition of departure attempts (morning of day 4, morning of day 5, then afternoon of day 5) mirrors the literary convention of escalating hospitality that reaches its limit at the third attempt. The father-in-law's hospitality has an element of self-interest (he is enjoying the company and the reconciliation) but the narrative presents it as genuinely generous rather than manipulative. His difficulty letting them go is the mirror opposite of Gibeah's failure to receive them.</p>",
    "8": "<p>On the fifth day they tarry until the afternoon — the Levite eats and is pressed to stay the night again. The afternoon departure is the final miscalculation: leaving in mid-afternoon rather than morning means they will not reach Bethlehem before dark and will need to find lodging en route. Ancient travelers calculated departure times based on the distance to the next safe stopping point; departing in the afternoon for a journey of more than a day meant spending the night at an intermediate point — in this case, Gibeah. The father-in-law's hospitality, ironically, has forced them into the dangerous overnight stop.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The afternoon departure scene has the father-in-law urging the Levite to spend one more night: 'the day has waned toward evening; please, spend the night.' The suggestion is sensible — nightfall is approaching, the journey is long, and stopping now avoids a dangerous night journey. But the Levite's refusal, with the servant's subsequent suggestion of Gibeah (v11), is driven by his reluctance to lodge in a non-Israelite city (Jebus, v12). The fatal irony: he refuses to stay in the safety of a Judahite father-in-law's home to avoid lodging among Jebusites, and ends up lodging among Israelites at Gibeah who prove more dangerous than any foreigner.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The Levite sets out toward Jebus (Jerusalem), which was still a Jebusite city at this point in the pre-monarchic period — hence the servant's description of it in v11 as 'a city of foreigners, who do not belong to the people of Israel.' The route from Bethlehem to Ephraim passed through the central hill country; Jebus/Jerusalem was roughly at the midpoint. The detail that the Levite has 'a couple of saddled donkeys' and that his concubine is with him specifies the party's composition — two donkeys (one for the concubine, one carrying provisions), the Levite, and a servant. A party of three with loaded animals was too small to be safely on the road after dark.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The servant suggests stopping at Jebus — 'Come, let us turn aside to this city of the Jebusites and spend the night in it.' The servant's pragmatism (night is falling; stop at the nearest city) is overridden by the master's ethnic preference (it's not an Israelite city; we should find an Israelite city to lodge in). The servant's suggestion proved wise in retrospect; the master's ethnic confidence — Israelite cities are safer — is the fatal assumption that the Gibeah narrative will catastrophically refute. The servant's voice (a minor character) turns out to carry the narrative's practical wisdom.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The Levite refuses: 'We will not turn aside into the city of foreigners, who do not belong to the people of Israel, but we will pass on to Gibeah.' The assumption behind the refusal is covenantal: Israelites share covenant obligations of hospitality with each other; foreigners do not. In the ancient Near East, ethnic and treaty relationships determined hospitality obligations. The Levite's logic is correct in theory — Israelites should be safer hosts for each other than Jebusites would be for Israelites. His error is not in the principle but in the assumption that Gibeah's inhabitants still observed covenant norms. The Gibeah narrative is specifically designed to shatter that assumption.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'Come and let us draw near to one of these places and spend the night at Gibeah or at Ramah.' The choice between Gibeah and Ramah was a choice between two Benjaminite towns on the road north from Jebus. Gibeah (Tell el-Ful, excavated by Albright) was the closer of the two — approximately 5 miles north of Jerusalem. Ramah was another 3 miles north. They chose Gibeah, the nearer option, because darkness was approaching. The narrative provides no indication that Gibeah was known for danger; it was simply the nearest town of Israel on their route. The tragedy is entirely unforeseeable from the travelers' perspective.</p>",
    "14": "<p>They arrive at Gibeah as the sun sets — the timing is precise and loaded. Sunset in the ancient world marked the transition from the relatively safe daylight period to the dangerous night; arriving at sunset meant they needed immediate hospitality. The city gate — where travelers arriving after dark would present themselves to be assessed and received — is where they sit. 'They sat down in the open square of the city, for no one took them into his house to spend the night.' The sitting in the open square is the visible sign of hospitality failure: in a functioning covenant community, no traveler should have to sit outside at nightfall.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The old man returning from his field at evening is the only person who offers hospitality — and he is not a native Gibeahite but a sojourner from Ephraim living in Benjamin. The irony is structural: the Levite had avoided lodging with Jebusites (foreigners) to find an Israelite host; the one Israelite who hosts him is himself a foreigner-within-Israel, an Ephraimite living among Benjaminites. The covenant failure at Gibeah is illustrated in microcosm by the fact that genuine hospitality comes only from a resident alien, not from the native population. The geographic and ethnic categories that the Levite trusted have been inverted.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'The old man lifted up his eyes and saw the traveler in the open square of the city.' The detail 'lifted up his eyes' (<em>wayyiśśā ʾet-ʿênāyw</em>) is an attentive-observation formula that appears in Genesis at moments of recognition and encounter (Gen 13:10; 18:2; 22:4). The old man's active noticing stands in contrast to all the other citizens of Gibeah who either did not notice or chose not to respond to the travelers sitting in the open square. His question — 'Where are you going? Where do you come from?' — is the standard hospitality-assessment question (cf. Gen 32:17; Judg 13:6).</p>",
    "18": "<p>The Levite identifies himself as from Bethlehem-Judah, traveling to 'the remote parts of the hill country of Ephraim' — his home territory — and explains that 'no one has taken me into his house.' The explicit statement that no one has received him is both a practical assessment and an implicit hospitality-shaming: in a functional covenant community, this statement would be a reproach to the entire city. The Levite also notes that he 'has straw and fodder for the donkeys, and bread and wine for myself and your female servant and the young man' — he is not asking for material provision, only for shelter, which makes Gibeah's failure even less defensible.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The detail that the Levite carries his own provisions — 'straw and fodder for the donkeys, and bread and wine for me and your female servant and the young man' — emphasizes his self-sufficiency. He is not asking to be fed; he asks only for a roof. This makes the lack of welcome even more indicting: the citizens of Gibeah cannot even offer shelter to self-provisioned travelers. In contrast, Abraham's hospitality to three strangers (Gen 18:1-8) involved running to meet them, preparing a feast, and standing in attendance — genuine proactive hospitality, not merely a minimal duty-discharge.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'Peace be to you; I will care for all your wants; only, do not spend the night in the square.' The old man's welcome — 'peace,' shalom — and his assumption of full responsibility for the party's needs mirrors the ideal hospitality protocol. His urgent warning 'do not spend the night in the square' suggests he already knows the danger the open square presents at night in Gibeah — he is not merely offering comfort but rescuing them from a known threat. Whether this knowledge came from previous incidents or from a general sense of the city's moral climate, his urgency underlines that Gibeah's violence is not an unprecedented anomaly but a recognized pattern.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The old man brings them in, provides fodder for the donkeys, washes their feet, and they eat and drink. The foot-washing is a standard hospitality gesture in the ancient Near East (Gen 18:4; 19:2; 1 Sam 25:41) — removing the road dust was both physically practical and socially symbolic, marking the traveler's transition from road-stranger to household guest. The shared meal that follows seals the hospitality bond; in the ancient world, eating together created a social obligation of mutual protection. The old man has done everything right; what happens next makes his hospitality irrelevant.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'No, my brothers, do not act so wickedly; since this man has come into my house, do not do this vile thing.' The old man's language — 'brothers,' 'do not do this vile thing' (<em>ʾal-taʿăśû ʾet-hannĕbālāh hazzōʾt</em>) — uses exactly the language of Lot's appeal in Gen 19:7-8. The word <em>nĕbālāh</em> (folly, outrage, vile act) is a technical legal term for acts that violate the fundamental social order (cf. its use in Gen 34:7 for Shechem's rape of Dinah; 2 Sam 13:12 for Amnon's rape of Tamar). The old man recognizes the men's demand as a <em>nĕbālāh</em> — a covenant-order violation — and invokes his hospitality obligation as the reason for refusal.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The old man's offer of his virgin daughter and the Levite's concubine instead is deeply troubling — he is willing to substitute female victims for his male guest. This offer exactly parallels Lot's offer of his daughters in Gen 19:8 and has been similarly problematic for interpreters across the centuries. The narrative does not editorially condemn or endorse the offer; its purpose is to establish the complete moral collapse of the period. The old man is the most sympathetic character in the Gibeah narrative, and even he acts in ways that modern and ancient readers have found deeply troubling — the text presents the entire society as morally broken without exception.</p>",
    "25": "<p>'But the men would not listen to him. So the man seized his concubine and made her go out to them.' The Levite himself pushes his concubine out to the mob — a detail more devastating than the old man's offer (which the mob refused). The Levite's action is explicitly self-preserving at the expense of the woman under his protection. The narrative offers no condemnation but the contrast is stark: the old man had honored his hospitality obligation to the guest; the Levite honors nothing. The concubine's assault occupies a single clause ('and they knew her and abused her all night until the morning') — the understatement is more horrifying than elaboration would be.</p>",
    "26": "<p>At dawn, the concubine falls at the door of the old man's house — she has crawled back to the threshold of the only shelter she had known. The specific detail of her falling at the doorway, with her hands on the threshold, has been interpreted as a last gesture of seeking the protection that had been taken from her. She is found there by her husband when he opens the door in the morning — the narrative's most brutal juxtaposition: the Levite sleeps through the night; the concubine is assaulted through the night. His morning departure behavior ('get up, let us go,' v28) adds callousness to cowardice.</p>",
    "27": "<p>'And her master rose up in the morning, and when he opened the doors of the house and went out to go on his way, behold, there was his woman lying at the door of the house.' The Levite's matter-of-fact departure preparation — 'opening the doors to go on his way' — as if the night had been uneventful — is the moral nadir of the narrative's characterization of him. He does not look for her; he simply opens the door and there she is. The word <em>nōpelet</em> (fallen, prostrate) is used for the dead in battle (e.g., Num 14:29, 32, 43). The reader is left uncertain about whether she is already dead or merely unconscious until the Levite's command in v28.</p>",
    "28": "<p>'Get up, let us be going.' Whether the concubine is alive or dead at this point is ambiguous — the Levite's command 'get up' suggests he thinks or hopes she may still be alive, but 'there was no answer.' His subsequent loading her onto the donkey and taking her home is the act of a man who has thoroughly failed her: he pushes her out to the mob, sleeps through her ordeal, commands her to rise as if she is a servant, and then transports her body home when she cannot respond. The NT's Good Samaritan parable (Luke 10:30-37) inverts every element of this scene: the one who should have protected (the Levite) abandons; the unexpected outsider rescues.</p>"
  }
}

